Shodan is a search engine that specializes in discovering Internet-connected Internet of Things (IoT) devices and other linked systems. It enables users to search for certain device types and display information about them, such as IP addresses, open ports, and software versions. Shodan can boost the security and awareness of IoT device manufacturers and distributors. Using Shodan, businesses may identify and safeguard any unprotected devices they have connected to the internet. In addition, Shodan may be used to monitor devices for vulnerabilities, enabling businesses to repair them promptly before they are exploited. However, attackers may also utilize Shodan to identify possible targets for cyberattacks. Using Shodan, attackers may search for certain sorts of devices, such as industrial control systems, and then use the acquired information to execute targeted assaults. In addition, attackers may utilize Shodan to locate susceptible devices, which they can then use as a springboard to launch attacks against other systems. Shodan may also be used to detect and reduce possible threats by defenders. Using Shodan, defenders may search for certain device types, such as industrial control systems, and then utilize the acquired data to detect and mitigate possible risks. Moreover, defenders may utilize Shodan to monitor devices for vulnerabilities, enabling them to repair them before they can be exploited. Due to the potential for misuse and the ease of locating vital infrastructure and other sensitive systems, CNN referred to Shodan in 2013 as "The scariest search engine on the Internet." Whether or not this is true now depends on one's viewpoint. Shodan has helped increase awareness of the security risks around IoT devices and linked systems, which may be a good thing, but it also gives an easy-to-use tool for attackers to locate susceptible equipment. Depending on its use, Shodan may be a potent weapon for both attackers and defenders. Companies that build and sell IoT devices may use Shodan to enhance security and raise awareness, while attackers can use it to locate insecure devices. Companies must be aware of the hazards and take measures to safeguard their equipment, and people must use Shodan appropriately. 